===Etymology===
{{clipping|en|vegetarian}} or {{m|en|vegetable}}, 1944.<ref>{{cite-journal|author={{w|Donald Watson}}|title=The Early History of the Vegan Movement|journal=The Vegan|url=http://issuu.com/vegan_society/docs/the-vegan-autumn-1965---21st-anniversary-issue|issue=Autumn|year=1965|pages=5–7}}</ref> {{coin|en|Donald Watson|nobycat=1}} of the {{w|The Vegan Society|Vegan Society}} and first appeared in ''The Vegan News''.<ref>{{cite-journal|author={{w|Donald Watson}}|title=Wanted – A Name|work=The Vegan News|year=1944|month=November|url=http://issuu.com/vegan_society/docs/the_vegan_news_1944|page=2|issue=1|passage=We should all consider carefully what our Group, and our magazine, and ourselves, shall be called. 'Non-dairy' has become established as a generally understood colloquialism, but like 'non-lacto' it is too negative. Moreover it does not imply that we are opposed to the use of eggs as food. We need a name that suggests what we do eat, and if possible one that conveys the idea that even with all animal foods taboo, Nature still offers us a bewildering assortment from which to choose. 'Vegetarian' and 'Fruitarian' are already associated with societies that allow the 'fruits'(!) of cows and fowls, therefore it seems we must make a new and appropriate word. As this first issue of our periodical had to be named, I have used the title "The Vegan News". Should we adopt this, our diet will soon become known as a VEGAN diet, and we should aspire to the rank of VEGANS. Members' suggestions will be welcomed. The virtue of having a short title is best known to those of us who, as secretaries of vegetarian societies have to type or write the word vegetarian thousands of times a year!}}</ref>

